logarithms.explanation:
To remove the logarithm, we exponentiate both sides of the equation. The logarithm is a natural logarithm, which means its base is $e.$ So, we use a base of $e$ for the exponentiation as well:
\begin{align*}
\ln \left( {3-7x} \right) &= 6 \\[3pt]
e^{\color{blue}\ln \left( {3-7x} \right)} &=e^{\color{blue}6}
\end{align*}
Since exponentiation is the inverse function of the logarithm, we get $e^{\ln(3-7x)} = 3-7x.$
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
3-7x & = e^6 \\[3pt]
- 7x &= e^6 - 3 \\[3pt]
x &= \dfrac{e^6 - 3}{ - 7} \\[3pt]
x &= \dfrac{3 -e^6}{7}.
\end{align*}

To remove the logarithm, we exponentiate both sides of the equation. The logarithm is a natural logarithm, which means its base is $e.$ So, we use a base of $e$ for the exponentiation as well:
\begin{align*}
\ln\left( {4x} \right) &= 2 \\[3pt]
e^{\color{blue}\ln\left( {4x} \right)} &=e^{\color{blue}2}
\end{align*}
Since exponentiation is the inverse function of the logarithm, we get $e^{\ln (4x)} = 4x.$
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
4x &= e^{2} \\[5pt]
x &= \dfrac{1}{4}e^{2}\\[5pt]
x &= \dfrac{e^{2}}{4}.
\end{align*}

First, we rearrange our equation to isolate the logarithmic term, as follows:
\begin{align*}
5\ln (7-2x) +13 &= 38 \\[3pt]
5\ln (7-2x) &= 25 \\[3pt]
\ln (7-2x) &= 5
\end{align*}
To remove the logarithm, we exponentiate both sides of the equation. The logarithm is a natural logarithm, which means its base is $e.$ So, we use a base of $e$ for the exponentiation as well:
\begin{align*}
\ln{(7-2x)} &= 5 \\[3pt]
e^{\color{blue}\ln{(7-2x)}} &=e^{\color{blue}5}
\end{align*}
Since exponentiation is the inverse function of the logarithm, we get $e^{\ln (7-2x)} = 7-2x.$
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
7-2x &= e^5 \\[5pt]
-2x &= e^5-7 \\[3pt]
x &= \dfrac{e^5-7}{-2} \\[3pt]
x &= \dfrac{7-e^5}{2}.
\end{align*}

First, we rearrange our equation to isolate the logarithmic term, as follows:
\begin{align*}
2\ln (1-5x) +3 &= 9 \\[3pt]
2\ln (1-5x) &= 6 \\[3pt]
\ln (1-5x) &= 3
\end{align*}
To remove the logarithm, we exponentiate both sides of the equation. The logarithm is a natural logarithm, which means its base is $e.$ So, we use a base of $e$ for the exponentiation as well:
\begin{align*}
\ln{(1-5x)} &= 3 \\[3pt]
e^{\color{blue}\ln{(1-5x)}} &=e^{\color{blue}3}
\end{align*}
Since exponentiation is the inverse function of the logarithm, we get $e^{\ln (1-5x)} = 1-5x.$
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
1-5x &= e^3 \\[5pt]
-5x &= e^3-1 \\[3pt]
x &= \dfrac{e^3-1}{-5} \\[3pt]
x &= \dfrac{1-e^3}{5}.
\end{align*}

First, we simplify our equation by collecting the like logarithmic terms, and isolating the logarithm, as follows:
\begin{align*}
\ln(x-1) - 3\ln(x-1) &= 2 \\[5pt]
(1-3)\ln(x-1) &=2 \\[5pt]
-2\ln(x-1) &= 2 \\[5pt]
\ln(x-1) &= -1
\end{align*}
To remove the logarithm, we exponentiate both sides of the equation. The logarithm is a natural logarithm, which means its base is $e.$ So, we use a base of $e$ for the exponentiation as well:
\begin{align*}
\ln(x-1) &= -1 \\[5pt]
e^{\color{blue}\ln(x-1)} &= e^{\color{blue}-1}
\end{align*}
Since exponentiation is the inverse function of the logarithm, we get $e^{\ln (x-1)} = x-1.$
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
x-1 &= e^{-1} \\[5pt]
x-1 &= \dfrac{1}{e} \\[5pt]
x & = \dfrac{1}{e} + 1.
\end{align*}

First, we simplify our equation by collecting the like logarithmic terms, and isolating the logarithm, as follows:
\begin{align*}
2\ln{x} + 3\ln{x} &= 20 \\[5pt]
(2+3)\ln x &= 20 \\[5pt]
5\ln x &= 20 \\[5pt]
\ln x &= \dfrac{20}{5}\\[5pt]
\ln x &=4.
\end{align*}
To remove the logarithm, we exponentiate both sides of the equation. The logarithm is a natural logarithm, which means its base is $e.$ So, we use a base of $e$ for the exponentiation as well:
\begin{align*}
\ln x &= 4 \\[5pt]
e^{\color{blue}\ln x} &= e^{\color{blue}4}
\end{align*}
Since exponentiation is the inverse function of the logarithm, we get $e^{\ln x} = x.$
Therefore, $ x = e^{4}. $

To find the instantaneous rate of change at a given point, we have to find $\dfrac {\textrm{d}y} {\textrm{d}x}$ at that point.
Taking the derivative, we have
\begin{align}
\dfrac{\textrm{d}y}{\textrm{d}x}&=\dfrac{\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}x}\left(\ln x +e^x\right)\\[5pt]
&=\dfrac{1}{x}+e^x \,.
\end{align}
Therefore, the instantaneous rate of change at $x=1$ is
\[
\eqalign{
\left.\dfrac {\textrm{d}y} {\textrm{d}x}\right|_{x=1}
&=\left.\left(\dfrac{1}{x}+e^x \right)\,\right|_{x=1}\\[5pt]
&=\dfrac{1}{1}+e^1\\[5pt]
&=1+e \,.
}
\]

Taking the derivative, we have
\begin{eqnarray}
\eqalign{
f'(x) & = \dfrac {\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}x} \left(2\ln x - 5e^x\right) \\[5pt]
& = 2\left(\dfrac {1}{x}\right) - 5e^x \\[5pt]
& = \dfrac {2}{x} - 5e^x.
}
\end{eqnarray}

To differentiate a logarithm with base $a,$ we use the formula
\[
\dfrac{\textrm{d}}{ \textrm{d} x}\left( \log_a x \right)= \dfrac{1}{x\ln a}.
\]
Therefore,
\begin{eqnarray}
\eqalign{
\dfrac {\textrm{d}} {\textrm{d}x} \left(2^{x} + \log_2 x\right)
& = 2^x \cdot \ln 2 + \dfrac {1}{x \cdot \ln 2} \\[5pt]
& = 2^x \ln 2 + \dfrac {1}{x \cdot \ln 2}.
}
\end{eqnarray}

