We use the change of base formula:
\[
\log_a X = \dfrac {\log_b X} {\log_b a}
\]
We want to change from base $a=81$ to base $b=3.$ So, we have
\begin{align}
\log_{81} x
& = \dfrac {\log_{3} x} {\log_{3} (81)} .
\end{align}
Rewriting the expression in the denominator using exponents, we get
\begin{align}
\dfrac {\log_3 x} {\log_3 (81)}
&=\dfrac {\log_3 x} {\log_3 (3^4)}\\[5pt]
&=\dfrac {\log_3 x} {4}.
\end{align}
Therefore, we conclude that
\[
\log_{81}x = \dfrac {\log_3 x} {4} = \dfrac{1}{4}\log_3 x .
\]

Let $f(x)=x^2+5x.$ Computing the derivative $f'(x)$ gives
\begin{align*}
f'(x) = \dfrac {\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}x} \left(x^2 + 5x\right)= 2x+5.
\end{align*}
We then compute $f'(-1)$, which gives
\begin{align*}
f'(-1) = 2(-1)+5 = 3 \,.
\end{align*}
Finally, we use the point-slope form with $m=3$ and the coordinates of our point $(-1, -4),$ and get
\begin{align*}
y - y_1 &= m(x-x_1) \\
y - (-4) &= 3(x-(-1)) \\
y +4 &= 3(x+1) \\
y & = 3x +3 -4\\
y &= 3x-1.
\end{align*}

Let $f(x)=x^2-3x.$ Computing the derivative $f'(x)$ gives
\begin{align*}
f'(x) = \dfrac {\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}x} \left(x^2 - 3x\right)= 2x-3.
\end{align*}
We then compute $f'(-2)$, which gives
\begin{align*}
f'(-2) = 2(-2)-3 = -7.
\end{align*}
Finally, we use the point-slope form with $m=-7$ and the coordinates of our point $(-2, 10),$ and get
\begin{align*}
y - y_1 &= m(x-x_1) \\
y - (10) &= -7(x-(-2)) \\
y - 10 &= -7(x+2) \\
y & = -7x - 14 +10\\
y &= -7x -4.
\end{align*}

quadratic-equations.explanation:
First, we solve for $x$ as follows:
\begin{align*}
x^2+q+3 &= 7 \\[3pt]
x^2 &= 7-q-3 \\[3pt]
x^2 &= 4-q \\[3pt]
\sqrt{x^2} &= \sqrt{4-q} \\[3pt]
\vert x\vert &= \sqrt{4-q}
\end{align*}
The equation has only one solution if the right-hand side is equal to zero, and the right-hand side is zero only if the expression underneath the radical is zero. So, we solve for the value of $q$ that makes the expression under the radical equal to zero:
\begin{align*}
4-q &= 0 \\[3pt]
q &= 4
\end{align*}
Therefore, $q=4$ will give only one solution to the equation.

