Let $f(x)=x^2+5x.$ Computing the derivative $f'(x)$ gives
\begin{align*}
f'(x) = \dfrac {\textrm{d}}{\textrm{d}x} \left(x^2 + 5x\right)= 2x+5.
\end{align*}
We then compute $f'(-1)$, which gives
\begin{align*}
f'(-1) = 2(-1)+5 = 3 \,.
\end{align*}
Finally, we use the point-slope form with $m=3$ and the coordinates of our point $(-1, -4),$ and get
\begin{align*}
y - y_1 &= m(x-x_1) \\
y - (-4) &= 3(x-(-1)) \\
y +4 &= 3(x+1) \\
y & = 3x +3 -4\\
y &= 3x-1.
\end{align*}

Let $f(x)=x^2-3x.$ Computing the derivative $f'(x)$ gives
